1. What is Stack?
👉 Stack is a linear data structure that follows the LIFO principle (Last In, First Out).
🎯 Interview Definition
👉 Stack is a class in Java that represents a LIFO data structure where the last inserted element is the first one to be removed.

Iterable
   ↓
Collection
   ↓
List
   ↓
Vector
   ↓
Stack

Stack extends Vector (inherits all its methods)
4. Important Methods in Stack
🔹 1. push()
push(E item)
👉 Adds element to top
🔹 2. pop()
pop()
👉 Removes and returns top element
🔹 3. peek()
peek()
👉 Returns top element without removing
🔹 4. empty()
empty()
👉 Checks if stack is empty
🔹 5. search()
search(Object o)
👉 Returns position from top
⚙️ 5. Other Inherited Methods (from Vector)
add(), remove()
get()
size()
isEmpty()
⏱️ 6. Time Complexity
Operation	Time
Push	O(1)
Pop	O(1)
Peek	O(1)

import java.util.*;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Stack<Integer> stack = new Stack<>();

        stack.push(10);
        stack.push(20);
        stack.push(30);

        System.out.println(stack.peek()); // 30

        System.out.println(stack.pop());  // 30

        System.out.println(stack);
    }
}

Stack vs Queue?
| Feature | Stack | Queue |
| ------- | ----- | ----- |
| Order   | LIFO  | FIFO  |
| Insert  | Top   | Rear  |
| Remove  | Top   | Front |

10. Limitations of Stack
Limited access (only top element) ❌
Stack overflow if too many elements ❌
Legacy class (extends Vector) ❌

1. What is Queue?
👉 Queue is a linear data structure that follows the FIFO principle (First In, First Out).
Queue is an interface in Java that represents a collection where elements are inserted at the rear and removed from the front
following FIFO order.

3. Position in Hierarchy
Iterable
   ↓
Collection
   ↓
Queue

👉 Important subinterfaces:
Deque (Double-ended queue)
👉 Implementations:
PriorityQueue
ArrayDeque
LinkedList

4. Key Features of Queue
✔ Follows FIFO
✔ Allows duplicates
✔ Ordered collection
✔ Used for processing tasks in sequence
✔ Can be implemented using arrays or linked lists

5. Important Methods in Queue
🔹 1. Adding Elements
✅ add(E e)
Inserts element
Throws exception if fails
queue.add(10);
✅ offer(E e)
Inserts element
Returns false if fails
queue.offer(20);
🔹 2. Removing Elements
✅ remove()
Removes front element
Throws exception if empty
queue.remove();
✅ poll()
Removes front element
Returns null if empty
queue.poll();
🔹 3. Accessing Elements
✅ element()
Returns front element
Throws exception if empty
queue.element();
✅ peek()
Returns front element
Returns null if empty
queue.peek();
⚖️ 6. Difference (Important for Interviews)
Method	Behavior on Empty
add()	Exception
offer()	false
remove()	Exception
poll()	null
element()	Exception
peek()	null
🧠 7. Types of Queue
🔹 1. Simple Queue
FIFO
🔹 2. Priority Queue

👉 Elements processed based on priority, not order

🔹 3. Deque (Double Ended Queue)

👉 Insert/remove from both ends

🚀 8. Example Program
import java.util.*;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Queue<Integer> queue = new LinkedList<>();

        queue.add(10);
        queue.add(20);
        queue.add(30);

        System.out.println(queue.peek()); // 10

        queue.poll();

        System.out.println(queue);
    }
}


⏱️ 9. Time Complexity
Operation	Time
Insert	O(1)
Remove	O(1)
Peek	O(1)

🧩 10. Real-Life Applications
🔹 1. CPU Scheduling
👉 Processes executed in order
🔹 2. Printer Queue
👉 First document printed first
🔹 3. Call Center Systems
👉 Calls handled in order

⚠️ 11. Limitations
No random access ❌
Only front/rear operations ❌
Less flexible than List ❌

🧠 12. Key Points to Remember
FIFO structure
Insert → rear
Delete → front
Methods: add, offer, remove, poll, peek
Implemented by LinkedList, PriorityQueue

🎯 Final Interview Answer
👉 Queue is a FIFO data structure in Java where elements are inserted at the rear and removed from the front using 
methods like add(), offer(), poll(), and peek().

